members.name: alignContent
members.descriptionHtml: Aligns a flex container's lines within the flex container when there is extra space in the cross-axis, similar to how justify-content aligns individual items within the main-axis.

members.name: alignItems
members.descriptionHtml: Sets the default alignment in the cross axis for all of the flex container's items, including anonymous flex items, similarly to how justify-content aligns items along the main axis.

members.name: alignmentAdjust
members.descriptionHtml: This property allows precise alignment of elements, such as graphics, that do not have a baseline-table or lack the desired baseline in their baseline-table. With the alignment-adjust property, the position of the baseline identified by the alignment-baseline can be explicitly determined. It also determines precisely the alignment point for each glyph within a textual element.

members.name: alignmentBaseline
members.descriptionHtml: Specifies how an object is aligned with respect to its parent. This property specifies which baseline of this element is to be aligned with the corresponding baseline of the parent. For example, this allows alphabetic baselines in Roman text to stay aligned across font size changes. It defaults to the baseline with the same name as the computed value of the alignment-baseline property.

members.name: alignSelf
members.descriptionHtml:
Aligns the box (as the alignment subject) within its containing block (as the alignment container) along the block/column/cross axis of the alignment container.

See CSS align-self property https://www.w3.org/TR/css-align-3/#propdef-align-self

members.name: animation
members.descriptionHtml: The animation CSS property is a shorthand property for the various animation properties: `animation-name`, `animation-duration`, `animation-timing-function`, `animation-delay`, `animation-iteration-count`, `animation-direction`, `animation-fill-mode`, and `animation-play-state`.

members.name: animationDelay
members.descriptionHtml: Defines a length of time to elapse before an animation starts, allowing an animation to begin execution some time after it is applied.

members.name: animationDirection
members.descriptionHtml: Defines whether an animation should run in reverse on some or all cycles.

members.name: animationDuration
members.descriptionHtml: Specifies the length an animation takes to finish. Default value is 0, meaning there will be no animation.

members.name: animationFillMode
members.descriptionHtml: The animation-fill-mode CSS property specifies how a CSS animation should apply styles to its target before and after its execution.

members.name: animationIterationCount
members.descriptionHtml: Specifies how many times an animation cycle should play.

members.name: animationName
members.descriptionHtml: Defines the list of animations that apply to the element.

members.name: animationPlayState
members.descriptionHtml: Defines whether an animation is running or paused.

members.name: animationTimingFunction
members.descriptionHtml: The animation-timing-function specifies the speed curve of an animation.

members.name: appearance
members.descriptionHtml: Allows changing the style of any element to platform-based interface elements or vice versa.

members.name: backdropFilter
members.descriptionHtml: Lets you apply graphical effects such as blurring or color shifting to the area behind an element. Because it applies to everything behind the element, to see the effect you must make the element or its background at least partially transparent.

members.name: backfaceVisibility
members.descriptionHtml: Determines whether or not the “back” side of a transformed element is visible when facing the viewer.

members.name: background
members.descriptionHtml: Shorthand property to set the values for one or more of: background-clip, background-color, background-image, background-origin, background-position, background-repeat, background-size, and background-attachment.

members.name: backgroundAttachment
members.descriptionHtml: If a background-image is specified, this property determines whether that image's position is fixed within the viewport, or scrolls along with its containing block. See CSS 3 background-attachment property https://drafts.csswg.org/css-backgrounds-3/#the-background-attachment

members.name: backgroundBlendMode
members.descriptionHtml: This property describes how the element's background images should blend with each other and the element's background color. The value is a list of blend modes that corresponds to each background image. Each element in the list will apply to the corresponding element of background-image. If a property doesn’t have enough comma-separated values to match the number of layers, the UA must calculate its used value by repeating the list of values until there are enough.

members.name: backgroundClip
members.descriptionHtml:
The background-clip CSS property specifies if an element's background, whether a `<color>` or an `<image>`, extends underneath its border.

\* Does not work in IE

\* The `text` value is experimental and should not be used in production code.

members.name: backgroundColor
members.descriptionHtml: Sets the background color of an element.

members.name: backgroundComposite
members.descriptionHtml: Sets a compositing style for background images and colors.

members.name: backgroundImage
members.descriptionHtml: Applies one or more background images to an element. These can be any valid CSS image, including url() paths to image files or CSS gradients.

members.name: backgroundOrigin
members.descriptionHtml: Specifies what the background-position property is relative to.

members.name: backgroundPosition
members.descriptionHtml: Sets the position of a background image.

members.name: backgroundRepeat
members.descriptionHtml: Background-repeat defines if and how background images will be repeated after they have been sized and positioned

members.name: backgroundSize
members.descriptionHtml: Sets the size of background images

members.name: border
members.descriptionHtml: Shorthand property that defines the different properties of all four sides of an element's border in a single declaration. It can be used to set border-width, border-style and border-color, or a subset of these.

members.name: borderBottom
members.descriptionHtml: Shorthand that sets the values of border-bottom-color, border-bottom-style, and border-bottom-width.

members.name: borderBottomColor
members.descriptionHtml: Sets the color of the bottom border of an element.

members.name: borderBottomLeftRadius
members.descriptionHtml: Defines the shape of the border of the bottom-left corner.

members.name: borderBottomRightRadius
members.descriptionHtml: Defines the shape of the border of the bottom-right corner.

members.name: borderBottomStyle
members.descriptionHtml: Sets the line style of the bottom border of a box.

members.name: borderBottomWidth
members.descriptionHtml: Sets the width of an element's bottom border. To set all four borders, use the border-width shorthand property which sets the values simultaneously for border-top-width, border-right-width, border-bottom-width, and border-left-width.

members.name: borderCollapse
members.descriptionHtml: Border-collapse can be used for collapsing the borders between table cells

members.name: borderColor
members.descriptionHtml: The CSS border-color property sets the color of an element's four borders. This property can have from one to four values, made up of the elementary properties: • border-top-color • border-right-color • border-bottom-color • border-left-color The default color is the currentColor of each of these values. If you provide one value, it sets the color for the element. Two values set the horizontal and vertical values, respectively. Providing three values sets the top, vertical, and bottom values, in that order. Four values set all for sides: top, right, bottom, and left, in that order.

members.name: borderCornerShape
members.descriptionHtml: Specifies different corner clipping effects, such as scoop (inner curves), bevel (straight cuts) or notch (cut-off rectangles). Works along with border-radius to specify the size of each corner effect.

members.name: borderImageSource
members.descriptionHtml: The property border-image-source is used to set the image to be used instead of the border style. If this is set to none the border-style is used instead.

members.name: borderImageWidth
members.descriptionHtml: The border-image-width CSS property defines the offset to use for dividing the border image in nine parts, the top-left corner, central top edge, top-right-corner, central right edge, bottom-right corner, central bottom edge, bottom-left corner, and central right edge. They represent inward distance from the top, right, bottom, and left edges.

members.name: borderLeft
members.descriptionHtml: Shorthand property that defines the border-width, border-style and border-color of an element's left border in a single declaration. Note that you can use the corresponding longhand properties to set specific individual properties of the left border — border-left-width, border-left-style and border-left-color.

members.name: borderLeftColor
members.descriptionHtml: The CSS border-left-color property sets the color of an element's left border. This page explains the border-left-color value, but often you will find it more convenient to fix the border's left color as part of a shorthand set, either border-left or border-color. Colors can be defined several ways. For more information, see Usage.

members.name: borderLeftStyle
members.descriptionHtml: Sets the style of an element's left border. To set all four borders, use the shorthand property, border-style. Otherwise, you can set the borders individually with border-top-style, border-right-style, border-bottom-style, border-left-style.

members.name: borderLeftWidth
members.descriptionHtml: Sets the width of an element's left border. To set all four borders, use the border-width shorthand property which sets the values simultaneously for border-top-width, border-right-width, border-bottom-width, and border-left-width.

members.name: borderRadius
members.descriptionHtml: Defines how round the border's corners are.

members.name: borderRight
members.descriptionHtml: Shorthand property that defines the border-width, border-style and border-color of an element's right border in a single declaration. Note that you can use the corresponding longhand properties to set specific individual properties of the right border — border-right-width, border-right-style and border-right-color.

members.name: borderRightColor
members.descriptionHtml: Sets the color of an element's right border. This page explains the border-right-color value, but often you will find it more convenient to fix the border's right color as part of a shorthand set, either border-right or border-color. Colors can be defined several ways. For more information, see Usage.

members.name: borderRightStyle
members.descriptionHtml: Sets the style of an element's right border. To set all four borders, use the shorthand property, border-style. Otherwise, you can set the borders individually with border-top-style, border-right-style, border-bottom-style, border-left-style.

members.name: borderRightWidth
members.descriptionHtml: Sets the width of an element's right border. To set all four borders, use the border-width shorthand property which sets the values simultaneously for border-top-width, border-right-width, border-bottom-width, and border-left-width.

members.name: borderSpacing
members.descriptionHtml: Specifies the distance between the borders of adjacent cells.

members.name: borderStyle
members.descriptionHtml: Sets the style of an element's four borders. This property can have from one to four values. With only one value, the value will be applied to all four borders; otherwise, this works as a shorthand property for each of border-top-style, border-right-style, border-bottom-style, border-left-style, where each border style may be assigned a separate value.

members.name: borderTop
members.descriptionHtml: Shorthand property that defines the border-width, border-style and border-color of an element's top border in a single declaration. Note that you can use the corresponding longhand properties to set specific individual properties of the top border — border-top-width, border-top-style and border-top-color.

members.name: borderTopColor
members.descriptionHtml: Sets the color of an element's top border. This page explains the border-top-color value, but often you will find it more convenient to fix the border's top color as part of a shorthand set, either border-top or border-color. Colors can be defined several ways. For more information, see Usage.

members.name: borderTopLeftRadius
members.descriptionHtml: Sets the rounding of the top-left corner of the element.

members.name: borderTopRightRadius
members.descriptionHtml: Sets the rounding of the top-right corner of the element.

members.name: borderTopStyle
members.descriptionHtml: Sets the style of an element's top border. To set all four borders, use the shorthand property, border-style. Otherwise, you can set the borders individually with border-top-style, border-right-style, border-bottom-style, border-left-style.

members.name: borderTopWidth
members.descriptionHtml: Sets the width of an element's top border. To set all four borders, use the border-width shorthand property which sets the values simultaneously for border-top-width, border-right-width, border-bottom-width, and border-left-width.

members.name: borderWidth
members.descriptionHtml: Sets the width of an element's four borders. This property can have from one to four values. This is a shorthand property for setting values simultaneously for border-top-width, border-right-width, border-bottom-width, and border-left-width.

members.name: bottom
members.descriptionHtml: This property specifies how far an absolutely positioned box's bottom margin edge is offset above the bottom edge of the box's containing block. For relatively positioned boxes, the offset is with respect to the bottom edges of the box itself (i.e., the box is given a position in the normal flow, then offset from that position according to these properties).

members.name: boxDecorationBreak
members.descriptionHtml: Breaks a box into fragments creating new borders, padding and repeating backgrounds or lets it stay as a continuous box on a page break, column break, or, for inline elements, at a line break.

members.name: boxShadow
members.descriptionHtml: Cast a drop shadow from the frame of almost any element. MDN: https://developer.mozilla.org/en-US/docs/Web/CSS/box-shadow

members.name: boxSizing
members.descriptionHtml: The CSS box-sizing property is used to alter the default CSS box model used to calculate width and height of the elements.

members.name: breakAfter
members.descriptionHtml: The CSS break-after property allows you to force a break on multi-column layouts. More specifically, it allows you to force a break after an element. It allows you to determine if a break should occur, and what type of break it should be. The break-after CSS property describes how the page, column or region break behaves after the generated box. If there is no generated box, the property is ignored.

members.name: breakBefore
members.descriptionHtml: Control page/column/region breaks that fall above a block of content

members.name: breakInside
members.descriptionHtml: Control page/column/region breaks that fall within a block of content

members.name: clear
members.descriptionHtml: The clear CSS property specifies if an element can be positioned next to or must be positioned below the floating elements that precede it in the markup.

members.name: clipRule
members.descriptionHtml: Clipping crops an graphic, so that only a portion of the graphic is rendered, or filled. This clip-rule property, when used with the clip-path property, defines which clip rule, or algorithm, to use when filling the different parts of a graphics.

members.name: color
members.descriptionHtml: The color property sets the color of an element's foreground content (usually text), accepting any standard CSS color from keywords and hex values to RGB(a) and HSL(a).

members.name: columnCount
members.descriptionHtml: Describes the number of columns of the element. See CSS 3 column-count property https://www.w3.org/TR/css3-multicol/#cc

members.name: columnFill
members.descriptionHtml: Specifies how to fill columns (balanced or sequential).

members.name: columnGap
members.descriptionHtml: The column-gap property controls the width of the gap between columns in multi-column elements.

members.name: columnRule
members.descriptionHtml: Sets the width, style, and color of the rule between columns.

members.name: columnRuleColor
members.descriptionHtml: Specifies the color of the rule between columns.

members.name: columnRuleWidth
members.descriptionHtml: Specifies the width of the rule between columns.

members.name: columns
members.descriptionHtml: This property is a shorthand property for setting column-width and/or column-count.

members.name: columnSpan
members.descriptionHtml: The column-span CSS property makes it possible for an element to span across all columns when its value is set to all. An element that spans more than one column is called a spanning element.

members.name: columnWidth
members.descriptionHtml: Specifies the width of columns in multi-column elements.

members.name: content
members.descriptionHtml: Content for pseudo selectors.

members.name: counterIncrement
members.descriptionHtml: The counter-increment property accepts one or more names of counters (identifiers), each one optionally followed by an integer which specifies the value by which the counter should be incremented (e.g. if the value is 2, the counter increases by 2 each time it is invoked).

members.name: counterReset
members.descriptionHtml: The counter-reset property contains a list of one or more names of counters, each one optionally followed by an integer (otherwise, the integer defaults to 0.) Each time the given element is invoked, the counters specified by the property are set to the given integer.

members.name: cue
members.descriptionHtml: The cue property specifies sound files (known as an "auditory icon") to be played by speech media agents before and after presenting an element's content; if only one file is specified, it is played both before and after. The volume at which the file(s) should be played, relative to the volume of the main element, may also be specified. The icon files may also be set separately with the cue-before and cue-after properties.

members.name: cueAfter
members.descriptionHtml: The cue-after property specifies a sound file (known as an "auditory icon") to be played by speech media agents after presenting an element's content; the volume at which the file should be played may also be specified. The shorthand property cue sets cue sounds for both before and after the element is presented.

members.name: cursor
members.descriptionHtml: Specifies the mouse cursor displayed when the mouse pointer is over an element.

members.name: direction
members.descriptionHtml: The direction CSS property specifies the text direction/writing direction. The rtl is used for Hebrew or Arabic text, the ltr is for other languages.

members.name: display
members.descriptionHtml: This property specifies the type of rendering box used for an element. It is a shorthand property for many other display properties. W3: https://www.w3.org/TR/css-display-3/#the-display-properties MDN: https://developer.mozilla.org/en-US/docs/Web/CSS/display

members.name: fill
members.descriptionHtml: The ‘fill’ property paints the interior of the given graphical element. The area to be painted consists of any areas inside the outline of the shape. To determine the inside of the shape, all subpaths are considered, and the interior is determined according to the rules associated with the current value of the ‘fill-rule’ property. The zero-width geometric outline of a shape is included in the area to be painted.

members.name: fillOpacity
members.descriptionHtml: SVG: Specifies the opacity of the color or the content the current object is filled with. See SVG 1.1 https://www.w3.org/TR/SVG/painting.html#FillOpacityProperty

members.name: fillRule
members.descriptionHtml: The ‘fill-rule’ property indicates the algorithm which is to be used to determine what parts of the canvas are included inside the shape. For a simple, non-intersecting path, it is intuitively clear what region lies "inside"; however, for a more complex path, such as a path that intersects itself or where one subpath encloses another, the interpretation of "inside" is not so obvious. The ‘fill-rule’ property provides two options for how the inside of a shape is determined:

members.name: filter
members.descriptionHtml: Applies various image processing effects. This property is largely unsupported. See Compatibility section for more information.

members.name: flex
members.descriptionHtml: Shorthand for `flex-grow`, `flex-shrink`, and `flex-basis`.

members.name: flexBasis
members.descriptionHtml: The flex-basis CSS property describes the initial main size of the flex item before any free space is distributed according to the flex factors described in the flex property (flex-grow and flex-shrink).

members.name: flexDirection
members.descriptionHtml: The flex-direction CSS property describes how flex items are placed in the flex container, by setting the direction of the flex container's main axis.

members.name: flexFlow
members.descriptionHtml: The flex-flow CSS property defines the flex container's main and cross axis. It is a shorthand property for the flex-direction and flex-wrap properties.

members.name: flexGrow
members.descriptionHtml: Specifies the flex grow factor of a flex item. See CSS flex-grow property https://drafts.csswg.org/css-flexbox-1/#flex-grow-property

members.name: flexShrink
members.descriptionHtml: Specifies the flex shrink factor of a flex item. See CSS flex-shrink property https://drafts.csswg.org/css-flexbox-1/#flex-shrink-property

members.name: flexWrap
members.descriptionHtml: Specifies whether flex items are forced into a single line or can be wrapped onto multiple lines. If wrapping is allowed, this property also enables you to control the direction in which lines are stacked. See CSS flex-wrap property https://drafts.csswg.org/css-flexbox-1/#flex-wrap-property

members.name: float
members.descriptionHtml: Elements which have the style float are floated horizontally. These elements can move as far to the left or right of the containing element. All elements after the floating element will flow around it, but elements before the floating element are not impacted. If several floating elements are placed after each other, they will float next to each other as long as there is room.

members.name: flowFrom
members.descriptionHtml: Flows content from a named flow (specified by a corresponding flow-into) through selected elements to form a dynamic chain of layout regions.

members.name: gridArea
members.descriptionHtml: Lays out one or more grid items bound by 4 grid lines. Shorthand for setting grid-column-start, grid-column-end, grid-row-start, and grid-row-end in a single declaration.

members.name: gridAutoColumns
members.descriptionHtml: Specifies the size of an implicitly-created grid column track

members.name: gridAutoFlow
members.descriptionHtml: Controls how the auto-placement algorithm works, specifying exactly how auto-placed items get flowed into the grid.

members.name: gridAutoRows
members.descriptionHtml: Specifies the size of an implicitly-created grid column track

members.name: gridColumn
members.descriptionHtml: Controls a grid item's placement in a grid area, particularly grid position and a grid span. Shorthand for setting grid-column-start and grid-column-end in a single declaration.

members.name: gridColumnEnd
members.descriptionHtml: Controls a grid item's placement in a grid area as well as grid position and a grid span. The grid-column-end property (with grid-row-start, grid-row-end, and grid-column-start) determines a grid item's placement by specifying the grid lines of a grid item's grid area.

members.name: gridColumnGap
members.descriptionHtml: Sets the size of the gap (gutter) between an element's columns

members.name: gridColumnStart
members.descriptionHtml: Determines a grid item's placement by specifying the starting grid lines of a grid item's grid area . A grid item's placement in a grid area consists of a grid position and a grid span. See also ( grid-row-start, grid-row-end, and grid-column-end)

members.name: gridGap
members.descriptionHtml: Specifies the gaps (gutters) between grid rows and columns. It is a shorthand for grid-row-gap and grid-column-gap.

members.name: gridRow
members.descriptionHtml: Gets or sets a value that indicates which row an element within a Grid should appear in. Shorthand for setting grid-row-start and grid-row-end in a single declaration.

members.name: gridRowEnd
members.descriptionHtml: Determines a grid item’s placement by specifying the block-end. A grid item's placement in a grid area consists of a grid position and a grid span. The grid-row-end property (with grid-row-start, grid-column-start, and grid-column-end) determines a grid item's placement by specifying the grid lines of a grid item's grid area.

members.name: gridRowGap
members.descriptionHtml: Sets the size of the gap (gutter) between an element's grid rows

members.name: gridRowPosition
members.descriptionHtml: Specifies a row position based upon an integer location, string value, or desired row size. css/properties/grid-row is used as short-hand for grid-row-position and grid-row-position

members.name: gridRowStart
members.descriptionHtml: Specifies a grid item’s start position within the grid row by contributing a line, a span, or nothing (automatic) to its grid placement, thereby specifying the inline-start edge of its grid area

members.name: gridTemplate
members.descriptionHtml: Specifies named grid areas which are not associated with any particular grid item, but can be referenced from the grid-placement properties. The syntax of the grid-template-areas property also provides a visualization of the structure of the grid, making the overall layout of the grid container easier to understand.

members.name: gridTemplateAreas
members.descriptionHtml: Specifies named grid areas

members.name: gridTemplateColumns
members.descriptionHtml: Specifies (with grid-template-rows) the line names and track sizing functions of the grid. Each sizing function can be specified as a length, a percentage of the grid container’s size, a measurement of the contents occupying the column or row, or a fraction of the free space in the grid.

members.name: gridTemplateRows
members.descriptionHtml: Specifies (with grid-template-columns) the line names and track sizing functions of the grid. Each sizing function can be specified as a length, a percentage of the grid container’s size, a measurement of the contents occupying the column or row, or a fraction of the free space in the grid.

members.name: height
members.descriptionHtml: Sets the height of an element. The content area of the element height does not include the padding, border, and margin of the element.

members.name: hyphenateLimitChars
members.descriptionHtml: Specifies the minimum number of characters in a hyphenated word

members.name: hyphenateLimitLines
members.descriptionHtml: Indicates the maximum number of successive hyphenated lines in an element. The ‘no-limit’ value means that there is no limit.

members.name: hyphenateLimitZone
members.descriptionHtml: Specifies the maximum amount of trailing whitespace (before justification) that may be left in a line before hyphenation is triggered to pull part of a word from the next line back up into the current one.

members.name: hyphens
members.descriptionHtml: Specifies whether or not words in a sentence can be split by the use of a manual or automatic hyphenation mechanism.

members.name: justifyContent
members.descriptionHtml: Defines how the browser distributes space between and around flex items along the main-axis of their container. See CSS justify-content property https://www.w3.org/TR/css-flexbox-1/#justify-content-property

members.name: justifySelf
members.descriptionHtml:
Justifies the box (as the alignment subject) within its containing block (as the alignment container) along the inline/row/main axis of the alignment container.

See CSS jusitfy-self property https://www.w3.org/TR/css-align-3/#propdef-justify-self

members.name: left
members.descriptionHtml: Sets the left position of an element relative to the nearest anscestor that is set to position absolute, relative, or fixed.

members.name: letterSpacing
members.descriptionHtml: The letter-spacing CSS property specifies the spacing behavior between text characters.

members.name: lineHeight
members.descriptionHtml: Specifies the height of an inline block level element. See CSS 2.1 line-height property https://www.w3.org/TR/CSS21/visudet.html#propdef-line-height

members.name: listStyle
members.descriptionHtml: Shorthand property that sets the list-style-type, list-style-position and list-style-image properties in one declaration.

members.name: listStyleImage
members.descriptionHtml: This property sets the image that will be used as the list item marker. When the image is available, it will replace the marker set with the 'list-style-type' marker. That also means that if the image is not available, it will show the style specified by list-style-property

members.name: listStylePosition
members.descriptionHtml: Specifies if the list-item markers should appear inside or outside the content flow.

members.name: listStyleType
members.descriptionHtml: Specifies the type of list-item marker in a list.

members.name: margin
members.descriptionHtml: The margin property is shorthand to allow you to set all four margins of an element at once. Its equivalent longhand properties are margin-top, margin-right, margin-bottom and margin-left. Negative values are also allowed.

members.name: marginBottom
members.descriptionHtml: margin-bottom sets the bottom margin of an element.

members.name: marginLeft
members.descriptionHtml: margin-left sets the left margin of an element.

members.name: marginRight
members.descriptionHtml: margin-right sets the right margin of an element.

members.name: marginTop
members.descriptionHtml: margin-top sets the top margin of an element.

members.name: marqueeDirection
members.descriptionHtml: The marquee-direction determines the initial direction in which the marquee content moves.

members.name: marqueeStyle
members.descriptionHtml: The 'marquee-style' property determines a marquee's scrolling behavior.

members.name: mask
members.descriptionHtml: This property is shorthand for setting mask-image, mask-mode, mask-repeat, mask-position, mask-clip, mask-origin, mask-composite and mask-size. Omitted values are set to their original properties' initial values.

members.name: maskBorder
members.descriptionHtml: This property is shorthand for setting mask-border-source, mask-border-slice, mask-border-width, mask-border-outset, and mask-border-repeat. Omitted values are set to their original properties' initial values.

members.name: maskBorderRepeat
members.descriptionHtml: This property specifies how the images for the sides and the middle part of the mask image are scaled and tiled. The first keyword applies to the horizontal sides, the second one applies to the vertical ones. If the second keyword is absent, it is assumed to be the same as the first, similar to the CSS border-image-repeat property.

members.name: maskBorderSlice
members.descriptionHtml: This property specifies inward offsets from the top, right, bottom, and left edges of the mask image, dividing it into nine regions: four corners, four edges, and a middle. The middle image part is discarded and treated as fully transparent black unless the fill keyword is present. The four values set the top, right, bottom and left offsets in that order, similar to the CSS border-image-slice property.

members.name: maskBorderSource
members.descriptionHtml: Specifies an image to be used as a mask. An image that is empty, fails to download, is non-existent, or cannot be displayed is ignored and does not mask the element.

members.name: maskBorderWidth
members.descriptionHtml: This property sets the width of the mask box image, similar to the CSS border-image-width property.

members.name: maskClip
members.descriptionHtml: Determines the mask painting area, which defines the area that is affected by the mask. The painted content of an element may be restricted to this area.

members.name: maskOrigin
members.descriptionHtml: For elements rendered as a single box, specifies the mask positioning area. For elements rendered as multiple boxes (e.g., inline boxes on several lines, boxes on several pages) specifies which boxes box-decoration-break operates on to determine the mask positioning area(s).

members.name: maxFontSize
members.descriptionHtml: This property must not be used. It is no longer included in any standard or standard track specification, nor is it implemented in any browser. It is only used when the text-align-last property is set to size. It controls allowed adjustments of font-size to fit line content.

members.name: maxHeight
members.descriptionHtml: Sets the maximum height for an element. It prevents the height of the element to exceed the specified value. If min-height is specified and is greater than max-height, max-height is overridden.

members.name: maxWidth
members.descriptionHtml: Sets the maximum width for an element. It limits the width property to be larger than the value specified in max-width.

members.name: minHeight
members.descriptionHtml: Sets the minimum height for an element. It prevents the height of the element to be smaller than the specified value. The value of min-height overrides both max-height and height.

members.name: minWidth
members.descriptionHtml: Sets the minimum width of an element. It limits the width property to be not smaller than the value specified in min-width.

members.name: mixBlendMode
members.descriptionHtml: The mix-blend-mode CSS property describes how an element's content should blend with the content of the element's direct parent and the element's background.

members.name: MozOsxFontSmoothing
members.descriptionHtml: (Moz specific) font smoothing directive.

members.name: MsHighContrastAdjust
members.descriptionHtml: (Ms specific) constrast adjust rule.

members.name: objectFit
members.descriptionHtml: The ‘object-fit’ property specifies how the contents of a replaced element should be fitted to the box established by its used height and width. See CSS 3 object-fit property https://www.w3.org/TR/css3-images/#the-object-fit

members.name: opacity
members.descriptionHtml: Specifies the transparency of an element. See CSS 3 opacity property https://drafts.csswg.org/css-color-3/#opacity

members.name: order
members.descriptionHtml: Specifies the order used to lay out flex items in their flex container. Elements are laid out in the ascending order of the order value. See CSS order property https://drafts.csswg.org/css-flexbox-1/#order-property

members.name: orphans
members.descriptionHtml: In paged media, this property defines the minimum number of lines in a block container that must be left at the bottom of the page. See CSS 3 orphans, widows properties https://drafts.csswg.org/css-break-3/#widows-orphans

members.name: outline
members.descriptionHtml: The CSS outline property is a shorthand property for setting one or more of the individual outline properties outline-style, outline-width and outline-color in a single rule. In most cases the use of this shortcut is preferable and more convenient. Outlines differ from borders in the following ways: • Outlines do not take up space, they are drawn above the content. • Outlines may be non-rectangular. They are rectangular in Gecko/Firefox. Internet Explorer attempts to place the smallest contiguous outline around all elements or shapes that are indicated to have an outline. Opera draws a non-rectangular shape around a construct.

members.name: outlineColor
members.descriptionHtml: The outline-color property sets the color of the outline of an element. An outline is a line that is drawn around elements, outside the border edge, to make the element stand out.

members.name: outlineOffset
members.descriptionHtml: The outline-offset property offsets the outline and draw it beyond the border edge.

members.name: overflow
members.descriptionHtml: The overflow property controls how extra content exceeding the bounding box of an element is rendered. It can be used in conjunction with an element that has a fixed width and height, to eliminate text-induced page distortion.

members.name: overflowStyle
members.descriptionHtml: Specifies the preferred scrolling methods for elements that overflow.

members.name: overflowWrap
members.descriptionHtml: Specifies whether or not the browser should insert line breaks within words to prevent text from overflowing its content box. In contrast to word-break, overflow-wrap will only create a break if an entire word cannot be placed on its own line without overflowing.

members.name: overflowX
members.descriptionHtml: Controls how extra content exceeding the x-axis of the bounding box of an element is rendered.

members.name: overflowY
members.descriptionHtml: Controls how extra content exceeding the y-axis of the bounding box of an element is rendered.

members.name: padding
members.descriptionHtml: The padding optional CSS property sets the required padding space on one to four sides of an element. The padding area is the space between an element and its border. Negative values are not allowed but decimal values are permitted. The element size is treated as fixed, and the content of the element shifts toward the center as padding is increased. The padding property is a shorthand to avoid setting each side separately (padding-top, padding-right, padding-bottom, padding-left).

members.name: paddingBlockEnd
members.descriptionHtml: The padding-block-end CSS property defines the logical block end padding of an element, which maps to a physical padding depending on the element's writing mode, directionality, and text orientation. It corresponds to the padding-top, padding-right, padding-bottom, or padding-left property depending on the values defined for writing-mode, direction, and text-orientation.

members.name: paddingBlockStart
members.descriptionHtml: The padding-block-start CSS property defines the logical block start padding of an element, which maps to a physical padding depending on the element's writing mode, directionality, and text orientation. It corresponds to the padding-top, padding-right, padding-bottom, or padding-left property depending on the values defined for writing-mode, direction, and text-orientation.

members.name: paddingBottom
members.descriptionHtml: The padding-bottom CSS property of an element sets the padding space required on the bottom of an element. The padding area is the space between the content of the element and its border. Contrary to margin-bottom values, negative values of padding-bottom are invalid.

members.name: paddingInlineEnd
members.descriptionHtml: The padding-inline-end CSS property defines the logical inline end padding of an element, which maps to a physical padding depending on the element's writing mode, directionality, and text orientation. It corresponds to the padding-top, padding-right, padding-bottom, or padding-left property depending on the values defined for writing-mode, direction, and text-orientation.

members.name: paddingInlineStart
members.descriptionHtml: The padding-inline-start CSS property defines the logical inline start padding of an element, which maps to a physical padding depending on the element's writing mode, directionality, and text orientation. It corresponds to the padding-top, padding-right, padding-bottom, or padding-left property depending on the values defined for writing-mode, direction, and text-orientation.

members.name: paddingLeft
members.descriptionHtml: The padding-left CSS property of an element sets the padding space required on the left side of an element. The padding area is the space between the content of the element and its border. Contrary to margin-left values, negative values of padding-left are invalid.

members.name: paddingRight
members.descriptionHtml: The padding-right CSS property of an element sets the padding space required on the right side of an element. The padding area is the space between the content of the element and its border. Contrary to margin-right values, negative values of padding-right are invalid.

members.name: paddingTop
members.descriptionHtml: The padding-top CSS property of an element sets the padding space required on the top of an element. The padding area is the space between the content of the element and its border. Contrary to margin-top values, negative values of padding-top are invalid.

members.name: pageBreakAfter
members.descriptionHtml: The page-break-after property is supported in all major browsers. With CSS3, page-break-* properties are only aliases of the break-* properties. The CSS3 Fragmentation spec defines breaks for all CSS box fragmentation.

members.name: pageBreakBefore
members.descriptionHtml: The page-break-before property sets the page-breaking behavior before an element. With CSS3, page-break-* properties are only aliases of the break-* properties. The CSS3 Fragmentation spec defines breaks for all CSS box fragmentation.

members.name: pageBreakInside
members.descriptionHtml: Sets the page-breaking behavior inside an element. With CSS3, page-break-* properties are only aliases of the break-* properties. The CSS3 Fragmentation spec defines breaks for all CSS box fragmentation.

members.name: pause
members.descriptionHtml: The pause property determines how long a speech media agent should pause before and after presenting an element. It is a shorthand for the pause-before and pause-after properties.

members.name: pauseAfter
members.descriptionHtml: The pause-after property determines how long a speech media agent should pause after presenting an element. It may be replaced by the shorthand property pause, which sets pause time before and after.

members.name: pauseBefore
members.descriptionHtml: The pause-before property determines how long a speech media agent should pause before presenting an element. It may be replaced by the shorthand property pause, which sets pause time before and after.

members.name: perspective
members.descriptionHtml: The perspective property defines how far an element is placed from the view on the z-axis, from the screen to the viewer. Perspective defines how an object is viewed. In graphic arts, perspective is the representation on a flat surface of what the viewer's eye would see in a 3D space. (See Wikipedia for more information about graphical perspective and for related illustrations.) The illusion of perspective on a flat surface, such as a computer screen, is created by projecting points on the flat surface as they would appear if the flat surface were a window through which the viewer was looking at the object. In discussion of virtual environments, this flat surface is called a projection plane.

members.name: perspectiveOrigin
members.descriptionHtml: The perspective-origin property establishes the origin for the perspective property. It effectively sets the X and Y position at which the viewer appears to be looking at the children of the element. When used with perspective, perspective-origin changes the appearance of an object, as if a viewer were looking at it from a different origin. An object appears differently if a viewer is looking directly at it versus looking at it from below, above, or from the side. Thus, the perspective-origin is like a vanishing point. The default value of perspective-origin is 50% 50%. This displays an object as if the viewer's eye were positioned directly at the center of the screen, both top-to-bottom and left-to-right. A value of 0% 0% changes the object as if the viewer was looking toward the top left angle. A value of 100% 100% changes the appearance as if viewed toward the bottom right angle.

members.name: pointerEvents
members.descriptionHtml: The pointer-events property allows you to control whether an element can be the target for the pointing device (e.g, mouse, pen) events.

members.name: position
members.descriptionHtml: The position property controls the type of positioning used by an element within its parent elements. The effect of the position property depends on a lot of factors, for example the position property of parent elements.

members.name: quotes
members.descriptionHtml: Sets the type of quotation marks for embedded quotations.

members.name: regionFragment
members.descriptionHtml: Controls whether the last region in a chain displays additional 'overset' content according its default overflow property, or if it displays a fragment of content as if it were flowing into a subsequent region.

members.name: resize
members.descriptionHtml: The resize CSS sets whether an element is resizable, and if so, in which direction(s).

members.name: restAfter
members.descriptionHtml: The rest-after property determines how long a speech media agent should pause after presenting an element's main content, before presenting that element's exit cue sound. It may be replaced by the shorthand property rest, which sets rest time before and after.

members.name: restBefore
members.descriptionHtml: The rest-before property determines how long a speech media agent should pause after presenting an intro cue sound for an element, before presenting that element's main content. It may be replaced by the shorthand property rest, which sets rest time before and after.

members.name: right
members.descriptionHtml: Specifies the position an element in relation to the right side of the containing element.

members.name: shapeImageThreshold
members.descriptionHtml: Defines the alpha channel threshold used to extract a shape from an image. Can be thought of as a "minimum opacity" threshold; that is, a value of 0.5 means that the shape will enclose all the pixels that are more than 50% opaque.

members.name: shapeInside
members.descriptionHtml: A future level of CSS Shapes will define a shape-inside property, which will define a shape to wrap content within the element. See Editor's Draft http://dev.w3.org/csswg/css-shapes and CSSWG wiki page on next-level plans http://wiki.csswg.org/spec/css-shapes

members.name: shapeMargin
members.descriptionHtml: Adds a margin to a shape-outside. In effect, defines a new shape that is the smallest contour around all the points that are the shape-margin distance outward perpendicular to each point on the underlying shape. For points where a perpendicular direction is not defined (e.g., a triangle corner), takes all points on a circle centered at the point and with a radius of the shape-margin distance. This property accepts only non-negative values.

members.name: shapeOutside
members.descriptionHtml: Declares a shape around which text should be wrapped, with possible modifications from the shape-margin property. The shape defined by shape-outside and shape-margin changes the geometry of a float element's float area.

members.name: speak
members.descriptionHtml: The speak property determines whether or not a speech synthesizer will read aloud the contents of an element.

members.name: speakAs
members.descriptionHtml: The speak-as property determines how the speech synthesizer interprets the content: words as whole words or as a sequence of letters, numbers as a numerical value or a sequence of digits, punctuation as pauses in speech or named punctuation characters.

members.name: stroke
members.descriptionHtml: The stroke property in CSS is for adding a border to SVG shapes. See SVG 1.1 https://www.w3.org/TR/SVG/painting.html#Stroke

members.name: strokeLinecap
members.descriptionHtml: SVG: The stroke-linecap attribute defines the shape to be used at the end of open subpaths when they are stroked. See SVG 1.1 https://www.w3.org/TR/SVG/painting.html#LineCaps

members.name: strokeOpacity
members.descriptionHtml: SVG: Specifies the opacity of the outline on the current object. See SVG 1.1 https://www.w3.org/TR/SVG/painting.html#StrokeOpacityProperty

members.name: strokeWidth
members.descriptionHtml: SVG: Specifies the width of the outline on the current object. See SVG 1.1 https://www.w3.org/TR/SVG/painting.html#StrokeWidthProperty

members.name: tableLayout
members.descriptionHtml: The 'table-layout' property controls the algorithm used to lay out the table cells, rows, and columns.

members.name: tabSize
members.descriptionHtml: The tab-size CSS property is used to customise the width of a tab (U+0009) character.

members.name: textAlign
members.descriptionHtml: The text-align CSS property describes how inline content like text is aligned in its parent block element. text-align does not control the alignment of block elements itself, only their inline content.

members.name: textAlignLast
members.descriptionHtml: The text-align-last CSS property describes how the last line of a block element or a line before line break is aligned in its parent block element.

members.name: textDecoration
members.descriptionHtml: The text-decoration CSS property is used to set the text formatting to underline, overline, line-through or blink. underline and overline decorations are positioned under the text, line-through over it.

members.name: textDecorationColor
members.descriptionHtml: Sets the color of any text decoration, such as underlines, overlines, and strike throughs.

members.name: textDecorationLine
members.descriptionHtml: Sets what kind of line decorations are added to an element, such as underlines, overlines, etc.

members.name: textDecorationSkip
members.descriptionHtml: Specifies what parts of an element’s content are skipped over when applying any text decoration.

members.name: textDecorationStyle
members.descriptionHtml: This property specifies the style of the text decoration line drawn on the specified element. The intended meaning for the values are the same as those of the border-style-properties.

members.name: textEmphasis
members.descriptionHtml: The text-emphasis property will apply special emphasis marks to the elements text. Slightly similar to the text-decoration property only that this property can have affect on the line-height. It also is noted that this is shorthand for text-emphasis-style and for text-emphasis-color.

members.name: textEmphasisColor
members.descriptionHtml: The text-emphasis-color property specifies the foreground color of the emphasis marks.

members.name: textEmphasisStyle
members.descriptionHtml: The text-emphasis-style property applies special emphasis marks to an element's text.

members.name: textHeight
members.descriptionHtml: This property helps determine an inline box's block-progression dimension, derived from the text-height and font-size properties for non-replaced elements, the height or the width for replaced elements, and the stacked block-progression dimension for inline-block elements. The block-progression dimension determines the position of the padding, border and margin for the element.

members.name: textIndent
members.descriptionHtml: Specifies the amount of space horizontally that should be left on the first line of the text of an element. This horizontal spacing is at the beginning of the first line and is in respect to the left edge of the containing block box.

members.name: textOverflow
members.descriptionHtml: The text-overflow shorthand CSS property determines how overflowed content that is not displayed is signaled to the users. It can be clipped, display an ellipsis ('…', U+2026 HORIZONTAL ELLIPSIS) or a Web author-defined string. It covers the two long-hand properties text-overflow-mode and text-overflow-ellipsis

members.name: textOverline
members.descriptionHtml: The text-overline property is the shorthand for the text-overline-style, text-overline-width, text-overline-color, and text-overline-mode properties.

members.name: textOverlineColor
members.descriptionHtml: Specifies the line color for the overline text decoration.

members.name: textOverlineMode
members.descriptionHtml: Sets the mode for the overline text decoration, determining whether the text decoration affects the space characters or not.

members.name: textOverlineStyle
members.descriptionHtml: Specifies the line style for overline text decoration.

members.name: textOverlineWidth
members.descriptionHtml: Specifies the line width for the overline text decoration.

members.name: textRendering
members.descriptionHtml: The text-rendering CSS property provides information to the browser about how to optimize when rendering text. Options are: legibility, speed or geometric precision.

members.name: textShadow
members.descriptionHtml: The CSS text-shadow property applies one or more drop shadows to the text and `<text-decorations>` of an element. Each shadow is specified as an offset from the text, along with optional color and blur radius values.

members.name: textTransform
members.descriptionHtml: This property transforms text for styling purposes. (It has no effect on the underlying content.)

members.name: textUnderlinePosition
members.descriptionHtml: Unsupported. This property will add a underline position value to the element that has an underline defined.

members.name: textUnderlineStyle
members.descriptionHtml: After review this should be replaced by text-decoration should it not? This property will set the underline style for text with a line value for underline, overline, and line-through.

members.name: top
members.descriptionHtml: This property specifies how far an absolutely positioned box's top margin edge is offset below the top edge of the box's containing block. For relatively positioned boxes, the offset is with respect to the top edges of the box itself (i.e., the box is given a position in the normal flow, then offset from that position according to these properties).

members.name: touchAction
members.descriptionHtml: Determines whether touch input may trigger default behavior supplied by the user agent, such as panning or zooming.

members.name: transform
members.descriptionHtml: CSS transforms allow elements styled with CSS to be transformed in two-dimensional or three-dimensional space. Using this property, elements can be translated, rotated, scaled, and skewed. The value list may consist of 2D and/or 3D transform values.

members.name: transformOrigin
members.descriptionHtml: This property defines the origin of the transformation axes relative to the element to which the transformation is applied.

members.name: transformOriginZ
members.descriptionHtml: This property allows you to define the relative position of the origin of the transformation grid along the z-axis.

members.name: transformStyle
members.descriptionHtml: This property specifies how nested elements are rendered in 3D space relative to their parent.

members.name: transition
members.descriptionHtml: The transition CSS property is a shorthand property for transition-property, transition-duration, transition-timing-function, and transition-delay. It allows to define the transition between two states of an element.

members.name: transitionDelay
members.descriptionHtml: Defines when the transition will start. A value of ‘0s’ means the transition will execute as soon as the property is changed. Otherwise, the value specifies an offset from the moment the property is changed, and the transition will delay execution by that offset.

members.name: transitionDuration
members.descriptionHtml: The 'transition-duration' property specifies the length of time a transition animation takes to complete.

members.name: transitionProperty
members.descriptionHtml: The 'transition-property' property specifies the name of the CSS property to which the transition is applied.

members.name: transitionTimingFunction
members.descriptionHtml: Sets the pace of action within a transition

members.name: unicodeBidi
members.descriptionHtml: The unicode-bidi CSS property specifies the level of embedding with respect to the bidirectional algorithm.

members.name: userFocus
members.descriptionHtml: This is for all the high level UX stuff.

members.name: userInput
members.descriptionHtml: For inputing user content

members.name: userSelect
members.descriptionHtml: Defines the text selection behavior.

members.name: verticalAlign
members.descriptionHtml: The vertical-align property controls how inline elements or text are vertically aligned compared to the baseline. If this property is used on table-cells it controls the vertical alignment of content of the table cell.

members.name: visibility
members.descriptionHtml: The visibility property specifies whether the boxes generated by an element are rendered.

members.name: voiceBalance
members.descriptionHtml: The voice-balance property sets the apparent position (in stereo sound) of the synthesized voice for spoken media.

members.name: voiceDuration
members.descriptionHtml: The voice-duration property allows the author to explicitly set the amount of time it should take a speech synthesizer to read an element's content, for example to allow the speech to be synchronized with other media. With a value of auto (the default) the length of time it takes to read the content is determined by the content itself and the voice-rate property.

members.name: voiceFamily
members.descriptionHtml: The voice-family property sets the speaker's voice used by a speech media agent to read an element. The speaker may be specified as a named character (to match a voice option in the speech reading software) or as a generic description of the age and gender of the voice. Similar to the font-family property for visual media, a comma-separated list of fallback options may be given in case the speech reader does not recognize the character name or cannot synthesize the requested combination of generic properties.

members.name: voicePitch
members.descriptionHtml: The voice-pitch property sets pitch or tone (high or low) for the synthesized speech when reading an element; the pitch may be specified absolutely or relative to the normal pitch for the voice-family used to read the text.

members.name: voiceRange
members.descriptionHtml: The voice-range property determines how much variation in pitch or tone will be created by the speech synthesize when reading an element. Emphasized text, grammatical structures and punctuation may all be rendered as changes in pitch, this property determines how strong or obvious those changes are; large ranges are associated with enthusiastic or emotional speech, while small ranges are associated with flat or mechanical speech.

members.name: voiceRate
members.descriptionHtml: The voice-rate property sets the speed at which the voice synthesized by a speech media agent will read content.

members.name: voiceStress
members.descriptionHtml: The voice-stress property sets the level of vocal emphasis to be used for synthesized speech reading the element.

members.name: voiceVolume
members.descriptionHtml: The voice-volume property sets the volume for spoken content in speech media. It replaces the deprecated volume property.

members.name: WebkitBackdropFilter
members.descriptionHtml: Edge requires the -webkit prefix backdrop-filter.

members.name: WebkitFontSmoothing
members.descriptionHtml: (Webkit specific) font smoothing directive.

members.name: WebkitOverflowScrolling
members.descriptionHtml: (Webkit specific) momentum scrolling on iOS devices

members.name: whiteSpace
members.descriptionHtml: The white-space property controls whether and how white space inside the element is collapsed, and whether lines may wrap at unforced "soft wrap" opportunities.

members.name: widows
members.descriptionHtml: In paged media, this property defines the mimimum number of lines that must be left at the top of the second page. See CSS 3 orphans, widows properties https://drafts.csswg.org/css-break-3/#widows-orphans

members.name: width
members.descriptionHtml: Specifies the width of the content area of an element. The content area of the element width does not include the padding, border, and margin of the element.

members.name: wordBreak
members.descriptionHtml: The word-break property is often used when there is long generated content that is strung together without and spaces or hyphens to beak apart. A common case of this is when there is a long URL that does not have any hyphens. This case could potentially cause the breaking of the layout as it could extend past the parent element.

members.name: wordSpacing
members.descriptionHtml: The word-spacing CSS property specifies the spacing behavior between "words".

members.name: wordWrap
members.descriptionHtml: An alias of css/properties/overflow-wrap, word-wrap defines whether to break words when the content exceeds the boundaries of its container.

members.name: wrapFlow
members.descriptionHtml: Specifies how exclusions affect inline content within block-level elements. Elements lay out their inline content in their content area but wrap around exclusion areas.

members.name: wrapMargin
members.descriptionHtml: Set the value that is used to offset the inner wrap shape from other shapes. Inline content that intersects a shape with this property will be pushed by this shape's margin.

members.name: writingMode
members.descriptionHtml: writing-mode specifies if lines of text are laid out horizontally or vertically, and the direction which lines of text and blocks progress.

members.name: zIndex
members.descriptionHtml: The z-index property specifies the z-order of an element and its descendants. When elements overlap, z-order determines which one covers the other. See CSS 2 z-index property https://www.w3.org/TR/CSS2/visuren.html#z-index

members.name: zoom
members.descriptionHtml: Sets the initial zoom factor of a document defined by `@viewport`. See CSS zoom descriptor https://drafts.csswg.org/css-device-adapt/#zoom-desc
